"""
Riemannian Bilevel Meta-Learning on MiniImageNet
=================================================

Single-file implementation comparing five hypergradient estimators on a
5-way 5-shot meta-learning task with Stiefel-constrained backbone:

  Han et al. (2024), "A Framework for Bilevel Optimization on Riemannian
  Manifolds":
    - HINV     direct Hessian inverse (with tiny ridge for numerical safety)
    - CG       conjugate gradient on (H + ridge*I) v = grad_w f
    - NS       truncated Neumann series  v = alpha * sum_k (I - alpha H)^k g
    - AD       truncated automatic differentiation through the inner loop

  PL paper:
    - R-HJFBiO Riemannian Hessian/Jacobian-Free with spectrally-clipped
               pseudoinverse (kernel-preserving, Morse-Bott consistent)

Setup follows Section 4.2 of the PL paper:
  - 5-way 5-shot meta-learning
  - 4-block CNN backbone, 16 channels per layer
  - First two convolutional kernels constrained to Stiefel manifolds
        W1 in St(27, 16),   W2 in St(144, 16)
  - Lower level: ridge-regularized softmax classifier on 400-d features
  - Three regimes for the lower-level regularizer:
        strong_convex (lambda = 1e-2),
        tiny_lam      (lambda = 1e-6),
        pl_only       (lambda = 0)

Usage
-----
    1. Place this script next to the 100 wnid folders (n01532829/, ...).
    2. python meta_learning_riemannian.py
    3. First run builds a cache (miniimagenet_cache.pt). Re-runs reuse it.
    4. Results land in ./results/.

For a fast sanity check, set QUICK_MODE = True at the top. To run only a
subset of methods or regimes, use the METHODS / REGIMES env vars, e.g.
    METHODS=hinv,r_hjfbio python meta_learning_riemannian.py

Notes
-----
  - Seeded random 64/16/20 class split (not the canonical Ravi-Larochelle
    splits). Sufficient for an optimization-quality comparison.
  - The closed-form Hessian of (cross-entropy + L2) is used to avoid
    the cost of autograd.functional.hessian. eigh is the dominant cost
    per task at ~1-2 s on Mac CPU, ~50-200 ms on GPU.
"""

